1. Review the current code and supporting artifacts before proposing changes. Focus first on correctness risks, behavioral regressions, missing tests, and unclear interfaces.
2. Present findings ordered by severity with precise file references whenever possible.
3. Turn accepted findings into a prioritized improvement plan saved under `plans/YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md`.
4. Keep the plan implementation-ready: summarize the problem, proposed fixes, tests, and assumptions without turning it into a giant changelog.
5. If no significant findings remain, say so explicitly and note any residual testing or observability gaps.
